post_text: Today we remember the events that took place 19 years ago. As educators and parents it's important that we share the history of this tragedy with our children, so as a nation we never forget what took place not only on that day, but the days that followed. Human mankind came together as one and united. United to show the world we can not be broken and we will rise to face any challenge that is thrown at us.

post_text: As today marks our first day of summer, we would like to take a moment to wish everyone a happy and safe summer. We can not thank the Lincoln Park Community enough for their support throughout distance learning. To our students and parents thank you for your patience and your hard work. To our staff and teachers thank you for transforming your classrooms from a physical space to an engaging virtual environment within the matter of days. Everyone has gone above and beyond and we truly thank everyone. So as we start summer it's time to close your computers and take break and relax. If you haven't checked out our end of year celebrations they will continue to be posted on our website at https://www.lincolnparkboe.org/Content2/272. Thank you, Thank You, & Thank you!!!!

post_text: Thank you to the Lincoln Park Education Association Pride Committee for coordinating donations to our local frontline workers by the teachers and administrators of the Lincoln Park School District. On Tuesday, May 12th, Wednesday, May 13th, and Saturday, May 16th they provided meals for Doctors, Nurses, and Staff of the Chilton Memorial Hospital, the Lincoln Park Police Department, and the Lincoln Park Emergency Squad. They are also making a monetary donation to the Lincoln Park Food Pantry. A Special thank you to the Shoprite of Lincoln Park, 5 Brothers Bagels & Deli, and A & A Fine Foods for preparing all of the food. #frontlineworkers #supportlocalbusiness #LPSTRONG

post_text: Let’s help out our first responders, if you can, that are on the front lines of this pandemic #LPStrong
shared_text:
Lincoln Park EMS
March 30 at 8:18 PM ·

To help protect our volunteer members from COVID-19, Lincoln Park EMS is using its limited supply of personal protective equipment (PPE). The need to gear up with infectious control gowns, masks, gloves and goggles is higher than ever. If you have any extra PPE or N95 masks, please consider donating to Lincoln Park EMS. Donations can be dropped off at our Squad building located at 34 Chapel Hill Road. Our building is next to Borough Hall, the 3rd driveway up the hill from Boonton Tpke. Donations can be left in the vestibule. Help Our Volunteers Stay Safe! If we receive more PPE than we can use, we will pay it forward and share with other Lincoln Park First Responders, Chilton Medical Center and the Lincoln Park Care Center.

post_text: So we made it to the end of week 1 of our Virtual Learning. Thank you to the teachers, parents, and students for making the week successful. Lets all take a well deserved break from our devices and get outside to get some fresh air. Remember to maintain social distancing. Please try to refrain from emailing teachers over the weekend, they have earned a much deserved break and they will be back online by 10 am Monday morning. Have a restful weekend and be safe everyone!!

Here's a message from Optimum/Altice:

In response to the COVID-19/coronavirus pandemic, Altice USA has taken several steps to ensure that Americans within the communities we serve have reliable access to high-speed broadband connectivity to keep them connected to the people, information, and resources they rely on.

Altice USA is committed to helping schools and students stay connected during this unprecedented time. For households with K-12 and/or college students who may be displaced due to school closures and who do not currently have home internet access, we are offering our Altice Advantage 30 Mbps broadband solution for free for 60 days to any new customer household within our footprint.

Starting Monday, March 16, 2020, eligible households interested in this solution can call:

866-200-9522 to enroll in Optimum region

A message from our Superintendent--This morning the Lincoln Park schools were put on a Shelter in Place alert after the LP Police notified us that there was police activity in the area. Instruction continued as normal, but there were more staff monitoring in the hallways. The students were cooperative and well-behaved during this event. The police notified us that the event is over and dismissal will take place as it normally would.
Sincerely,
Jim Grube
